    "text": "![](https://www.naukri.com/code360/problems/possible-numbers_1466965?interviewProblemRedirection=true&page=2&company%5B%5D=Apple&sort_entity=recents&sort_order=DESC) ![](https://static.naukimg.com/s/0/0/i/transparentImg.png)\n![Naukri Code 360](https://files.codingninjas.in/new-cn-logos-1-1711622387.svg)\n  * Learn\n\n\n  * Contests & Events\n\n\n  * Interview prep \n\n\n  * Practice\n\n\n  * Resources\n\n\nLogin\nInterview problemsView all problems\nProblem\nSubmissions\nHints & solutions\nDiscuss\n#  ProRam Numbers \nHard \n![](https://files.codingninjas.in/yellow-spark-22969.svg)\n0/120 \nAverage time to solve is 45m \n[![profile](https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-9cinZAxtDzY/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/AKF05nA33ddvQyQwuCKcxVlGwX0JlWwqjg/s96-c/photo.jpg)](https://www.naukri.com/code360/profile/9e238f21-b223-4b94-9e9c-9089777a5feb)\nContributed by \nEkansh \n11 upvotes \nAsked in companies\n##  Problem statement \nSend feedback \nProRam is given an array of distinct ‘DIGITS’ sorted in ascending order. ProRam wants to know how many possible numbers can be formed from a ‘DIGITS’ array such that it is less than or equal to the given integer ‘N.' ProRam can use the digits from the ‘DIGITS’ array as many times as he wants. For Example:- ‘DIGITS’ = [1, 2, 3] . The possible numbers are 11, 1, 2, 3, 22, 221, 321, 123 etc.\nProRam is busy with some work. Can you solve this for ProRam to find the number of possible numbers formed from digit array which are less than or equal to ‘N’?\nDetailed explanation  ( Input/output format, Notes, Images ) \n**Input Format:** ```\nThe first line contains ‘T,’ denoting the number of test cases.\nThe first line of the test case contains two integers, ‘M’ and ‘N,’ denoting the size of the ‘DIGITS’ array and given number.\nThe second line contains ‘M’ space-separated distinct integers denoting the elements of ‘DIGITS.’\n\n```\n**Output Format:** ```\nFor each test case, a single line should contain an integer that denotes the total possible numbers which are less than or equal to ‘N.’\n\n```\n**Note:** ```\nYou do not need to print anything, and it has already been taken care of. Just implement the given function.\n\n```\n\n**Constraints:** ```\n1 <= ’T’ <= 10\n1 <= ‘M’ <= 9\n1 <= ‘N’ <= 10^9\n1 <= ‘DIGITS[i]’ <= 9\nWhere ‘DIGITS’ is sorted in ascending order, and values in the ‘DIGITS’ array are unique.\nTime Limit: 1 sec\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Input 1:\n```\n2\n3 45\n1 4 5\n3 11\n1 2 3\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Output 1:\n```\n9\n4\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Output Explanation:\n```\nFirst Test case:-\nPossible Numbers less than 45 which can be formed from [1 ,4 ,5] are 1, 4, 5, 11, 14, 15, 41, 44, 45.\nHence answer for the first test case is 9.\nSecond Test case:-\nPossible Numbers less than 11 which can be formed from [1, 2, 3] are 1, 2, 3, 11.\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Input 2:\n```\n2\n3 88\n1 4 6 \n2 89\n2 3 \n\n```\n\n##### Sample Output 2:\n```\n12\n6\n\n```\n\nC++ (g++ 5.4) \n![Full screen](https://static.naukimg.com/code360/assets/icons/controlled-timer.svg)\n1\n2\n3\n4\n#include<bits/stdc++.h>\nint possibleNumbers(int n, int m, vector<int>& digits) {\n// Write your code here.\n}\nEnter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview\nConsole \nPrev \nRun  Submit code \nNext \nSettings\nReset Code\nLayouts\nFull Screen Mode\nStart timer\n",
