    "text": "![](https://www.naukri.com/code360/problems/beautiful-vertices_3153025?interviewProblemRedirection=true&page=2&company%5B%5D=Microsoft&sort_entity=recents&sort_order=DESC) ![](https://static.naukimg.com/s/0/0/i/transparentImg.png)\n![Naukri Code 360](https://files.codingninjas.in/new-cn-logos-1-1711622387.svg)\n  * Learn\n\n\n  * Contests & Events\n\n\n  * Interview prep \n\n\n  * Practice\n\n\n  * Resources\n\n\nLogin\nInterview problemsView all problems\nProblem\nSubmissions\nHints & solutions\nDiscuss\n#  Beautiful Vertices \nHard \n![](https://files.codingninjas.in/yellow-spark-22969.svg)\n0/120 \n[![profile](https://files.codingninjas.in/avatar-1710924338.png)](https://www.naukri.com/code360/profile/c982ae85-652d-42d4-8506-42031874f36e)\nContributed by \nAbhinav \n3 upvotes \nAsked in companies\n![Uber](https://files.codingninjas.in/company-short-logo-url/776/2ab7f1d4a1d4cb7376d6a1ddc96a8016.png)![Microsoft](https://files.codingninjas.in/company-short-logo-url/14/a18b52c13a74e0d83f599b2be75d593b.png)![Accolite](https://files.codingninjas.in/company-short-logo-url/672/d8858264f44a00852f8f90c3ac557086.png)\n##  Problem statement \nSend feedback \nYou are given an undirected graph containing ‘N’ vertices that are connected by ‘M’ edges. Your task is to find the number of beautiful vertices. A vertex is beautiful if removing it will disconnect the graph, i.e., increase the number of connected components.\nFor Example:\n```\nYou are given ‘N’ = 5, ‘M’ = 5 and ‘EDGES’ = [[1, 2], [1, 3], [3, 4], [3, 5], [4, 5]]. \n\n```\n\n![](https://files.codingninjas.in/ar1-13843.png)\n```\nThe beautiful vertices in the given graph are ‘1’ and ‘3’. If we remove ‘1’, vertex ‘2’ will be disconnected from the connected component (‘3’↔’4’↔’5’). If we remove vertex ‘3’, we will get two disjoint connected components (‘1’↔’2’) and (‘4’↔’5’).\n\n```\n\nDetailed explanation  ( Input/output format, Notes, Images ) \n**Input Format :** ```\nThe first line of the input contains a single integer 'T', representing the number of test cases.\nThe first line of each test case contains two space-separated integers, ‘N’ and ‘M’, representing the numbers of vertices and edges, respectively.\nThe next line ‘M’ lines contain two space-separated integers representing an edge.\n\n```\n**Output Format:** ```\nFor each test case, print the number of beautiful vertices.\nPrint the output of each test case in a separate line.\n\n```\n**Note:** ```\nYou do not need to print anything. It has already been taken care of. Just implement the given function.\n\n```\n\n**Constraints:** ```\n1 <= T <= 10\n1 <= N <= 2000\n1 <= M <= N*(N-1)/2\n1 <= EDGES[i][0] <= N\n1 <= EDGES[i][1] <= N\nTime Limit: 1 sec\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Input 1:\n```\n2\n5 5\n1 2\n1 3\n3 4\n3 5\n4 5\n3 2\n1 2\n2 3\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Output 1:\n```\n2\n1\n\n```\n\n##### Explanation of Sample Input 1:\n```\nFor the first test case, the graph will look like this:\n\n```\n\n![](https://files.codingninjas.in/ar1-13843.png)\n```\nThe beautiful vertices in the given graph are ‘1’ and ‘3’. If we remove ‘1’, vertex ‘2’ will be disconnected from the connected component (‘3’↔’4’↔’5’). If we remove vertex ‘3’, we will get two connected components (‘1’↔’2’) and (‘4’↔’5’).\nFor the second test case, the graph will look like this:\n\n```\n\n![](https://files.codingninjas.in/ar2-13844.png)\n```\nThe beautiful vertex in the given graph is ‘2’. If we remove vertex ‘2’, we will get two disjoint components (‘1’) and (‘3’).\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Input 2:\n```\n2\n3 3\n1 2\n1 3\n2 3\n4 3\n1 2\n2 3\n3 4\n\n```\n\n##### Sample Output 2:\n```\n0\n2\n\n```\n\nC++ (g++ 5.4) \n![Full screen](https://static.naukimg.com/code360/assets/icons/controlled-timer.svg)\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\n#include<bits/stdc++.h>\nint beautifulVertices(int n, int m, vector<vector<int>> &edges)\n{\n// Write your code here.\n}\nEnter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview\nConsole \nPrev \nRun  Submit code \nNext \nSettings\nReset Code\nLayouts\nFull Screen Mode\nStart timer\n",
